== Japanese content ==
'''Morimoto Shrine''' (もりもとじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Osaka Prefecture|Q122723|qid=Q122723|1=Osaka Prefecture}}. There is one shrine of this name each in {{ill|lt=Habikino|Q694308|qid=Q694308|1=Habikino}} and {{ill|lt=Kashiwara|Q873583|qid=Q873583|1=Kashiwara}}; both are {{ill|lt=disputed identifications|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} of "Morimoto Shrine, two seats," a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myojin Taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}) of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Asuka District|1=UNKNOWN}} in {{ill|lt=Kawachi Province|Q1047150|qid=Q1047150|1=Kawachi Province}}. The Habikino Morimoto Shrine is considered the stronger candidate. It is said to grant blessings for cutting/enjoining relationships, naming, and divination.

=== Overview ===
Both include {{ill|qid=Q1107286|lt=Futsunushi|Q1107286|qid=Q1107286|1=Futsunushi}} among their enshrined deities. One theory says that in the era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|qid=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}}, Iwawakino-Mikoto, 14th-generation descendant of Futsunushi-no-Mikoto, lived at the place of Futsunushi's tomb and enshrined the ancestral deity there.

Besides being recorded as a myojin taisha in the Engishiki Jinmyocho, its festival is listed in the Engishiki as "Morimoto Festival," and emissaries from the Treasury Bureau attended. During the {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} era, when {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|qid=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}} attacked {{ill|lt=Takaya Castle|Q11669272|qid=Q11669272|1=Takaya Castle}}, shrine buildings and treasures were lost in war fire; in {{ill|lt=1586|Q6739|qid=Q6739|1=1586}} (Tensho 14), lands were confiscated by {{ill|lt=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|Q187550|qid=Q187550|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi}}, causing decline.

