=== Enshrined deities ===
It is said to enshrine the married pair Futsunushi-no-Mikoto and Futsunushi-hime-no-Mikoto, but ''Shrine Register'' records {{ill|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} and Futsunushi-no-Mikoto; ''Kawachi no Kuni Shikijin Shiko'' lists {{ill|lt=Kukunochi|Q10749920|qid=Q10749920|lt=Kukunochi-no-Mikoto|1=Kukunochi}} and {{ill|lt=Mizuhanome|Q8191796|qid=Q8191796|lt=Hiyatani-ni-imasu Mizuhanome-no-Kami|1=Mizuhanome}}; ''Place Name Dictionary,'' ''Jingi Shiryo,'' and ''Chiri Shiryo'' call it "the ancestral deity of the Tosoki no Sukune clan."

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown. Shrine tradition says the clan related to Iwawakino-Mikoto conducted rites, and in the Heian period called themselves "Yahagi Imiki." In the era of {{ill|lt=shinbutsu shugo|Q2279088|qid=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}}, shrine-temple Kongorin-ji was founded and served by shrine monks, but it was abolished by {{ill|lt=shinbutsu bunri|Q1970535|qid=Q1970535|1=Shinbutsu bunri}} in Meiji. It was ranked village shrine in Meiji 5 (1872), and became a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shinsen-heihaku-ryo kyoshinsha|1=UNKNOWN}} in Meiji 41 ({{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|qid=Q2056|1=1908}}).

=== Precincts ===
In front of the main hall stand a pair of stone objects called "Hayato stones." They are beast-head human-body carvings; date unknown, but closely resemble the first Hayato stone at "Nafuyama Tomb" in {{ill|lt=Nara|Q169134|qid=Q169134|1=Nara (city)}}<ref>{{Cite web|和書|title="Hayato Stone"|url=https://www.city.habikino.lg.jp/soshiki/shougaigakushu/bunkazaihogoka/bunkazai/iseki_shokai/kaisetsu/2466.html|website=Habikino City|accessdate=2019-10-04|language=ja}}</ref>.

